<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-166-010 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 905 652</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Office  May 1991 v113 n5 p14(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How fax boards can enhance network communications. (tutorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Corn, Richard F.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The latest facsimile boards can be installed on network servers sothat they can be used by anyone on a local area network.andP;  The faxserver boards use fast, intelligent microprocessors and improvedsoftware; the result is reduced cost, improved quality and greaterconvenience.andP;  A full-fledged fax server can be had by installing a$1,000 board on a $2,000 microcomputer.andP;  In many cases, such asetup is less costly than buying a fax machine.andP;  Most fax boardswill send text files in ASCII and DCA format and graphics files inPCX and TIFF formats.andP;  Microcomputer-based fax servers can also betied into minicomputer- and mainframe-based networks.andP;  The biggestadministrative problem for such networks is routing incomingfaxes.andP;  Unfortunately, fully automated routing technologies arenot here yet.andP;  Existing technologies for automated routing includedirect inward dialing (DID), which may be practical fororganizations with sophisticated telephone systems; opticalcharacter recognition (OCR) software, which encounters troublewhen handling hand-written cover sheets; and touch-telephonerouting.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Facsimile Boards/CardsLocal Area NetworksNetwork ManagementCost of CommunicationsTutorialCommunications Boards/Cards.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>